Cook the quinoa: Preheat the broiler to high or the #oven{} to 500 degrees. In a
#small pot{}, bring 1 cup water to a boil with a large pinch of @salt{pinch}. Once
boiling, add the @quinoa{1/2%cup}, cover, and reduce to a simmer for ~{15-20%minutes},
until tender. Fluff with a #fork{} and place in a #large bowl{} to cool.

Wash and dry all produce. Meanwhile, finely chop the @mint{1/4%oz}(finely chopped)
and half the @arugula{2%oz}. Mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}. Trim the @sugar snap peas{4%oz}, if necessary.

Make the arugula-mint pesto: In a #small bowl{}, combine the mint, chopped arugula,
and a large drizzle of @olive oil{drizzle}. Stir in a pinch of garlic and season
to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of olive oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Season the
@skin-on salmon{12%oz} on all sides with salt and pepper. Add the salmon to the
pan and cook for ~{3-5%minutes} per side, until just opaque throughout. Remove
and discard the skin, if desired.

While the salmon cooks, toss the snap peas on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle
of olive oil and a pinch of salt and pepper. Place the snap peas under the
#broiler{} for ~{4-5%minutes}, until slightly charred.

Toss the cooled quinoa with the remaining arugula, @almonds{1%oz}, 2 teaspoons
@whole grain mustard{2%tsp} (or less, to taste), and a drizzle of olive oil. Season
with salt and pepper.

> You can adjust the mustard amount to taste - start with 2 teaspoons or less.

Finish: Toss the snap peas with half the pesto. Plate the salmon alongside
the snap peas and quinoa salad. Drizzle the remaining pesto over the salmon
and enjoy!

> Peppery arugula and refreshing mint sub in for basil in this non-traditional
> pesto. It's the perfect accompaniment to rich, flaky salmon. You'll be shocked
> by how delicious sugar snap peas can be after a flash under the broiler - it's
> a veggie revelation!